==riddle_begins==
- <i>Many years ago, this forest was once the site of an ancient kingdom.</i>

<i>The king, on his deathbed, bequeathed his three sons each equal part of the kingdom and gifted each an item from his imperial regalia.</i>

*[A foolish decision]

- <i>Three thrones were set in place at the royal court, and for a while the brothers ruled peacefully,  side by side.</i>

*[But peace can only last so long...]

- <i>One day, a  man with a donkey entered the court seeking the brothers’ counsel. Each king sat resplendent in his signature colour, one in red, one in black and one in green.</i>

*[Easy enough to tell them apart]

- <i>There are many accounts of what happened that day, but all agree on the following: Firstly, the man spoke in a low voice,</i> 

*[Why was he there?]

- <i>The most cunning king in red leaned back and paused in contemplation. From the left, the black-robed king leapt up and made as if to strike the man. The final brother, in green, adjusted his crown nervously.</i>  

*[What did he say?]

- <i>The donkey at the old man’s side let out a long braying laugh, shattering the tense silence.</i>

*[What made the donkey laugh?]

- <i>At once, the king who had been gifted the imperial sword drew it and ran the brother next to him through. </i>
<i>The remaining king stood wide-eyed, looking over his slain brother’s body at the king with the sword. Unable to believe his own brother capable of such betrayal, he could not imagine the same fate would befall him. </i>

<i>His expression remained fixed in disbelief as his head fell from his body. </i>   

*[Why would brother betray brother?]

- <i>Two clattering sounds rang out, first the goblet, and then the crown. The king with the sword took the crown from where it lay, and lifted his other brother's goblet to toast the man as he led his donkey out of the castle and into the woods.</i>

*[As it always does, it ends with the woods]

- The station master opens her eyes. You don't remember her closing them. 

"And there it is. I'm sure you understand the pickle I'm in. I can't for the life of me figure out which brother did it. He had the sword obviosuly, but other than that it's a mystery. If you could figure out the answer to my little conundrum, I would be more than happy to tell you about your departing train." 

